TY  - JOUR
TI  - Online collection channel and government subsidy strategy of retired power batteries considering cascade utilization
AU  - Wen, Danping
AU  - Wang, Zhuangzhong
AU  - Wang, Min
AU  - Appolloni, Andrea
AU  - Xiao, Tiaojun
T2  - COMPUTERS & INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING
AB  - Recyclers have valued the cascade utilization of retired power batteries, and the advent of the online collection has prompted many recyclers to redesign the traditional collection channel to achieve a sustainable circular economy. This paper conducts a game-theoretic model to study the recycler's collection channel design, and further investigates the interplay between the collection channel and the government subsidy strategies. The subsidies for cascade utilization rate and online collection cost are examined. We find that (i) Engaging in online collection motivates the recycler to collect more retired power batteries, and can help the recycler achieve a win-win situation for both environment and economy under certain conditions. (ii) A high cascade utilization rate motivates the recycler to engage in online collection. When the additional management cost is low, a high consumers' preference for online collection or a low subsidy for online collection cost motivates the recycler to use dual collection channels. (iii) Under single online collection, the subsidy for online collection cost improves social welfare when the online collection cost is moderate. Under dual collection channels, a high cascade utilization revenue (rate) increases (decreases) the government's motivation to subsidize the cascade utilization rate. These findings offer guidance for collection channel redesign and the choice of subsidy strategy in the retired power batteries industry.
