TY  - JOUR
TI  - Research on supply chain optimization under different government subsidy strategies in the remanufacturing-insurance combination system
AU  - Liu, Bohai
AU  - Liu, Xian
AU  - Zhou, Tao
AU  - Zheng, Handong
AU  - Jin, Xiaobing
AU  - Li, Kai
T2  - EXPERT SYSTEMS WITH APPLICATIONS
AB  - Remanufacturing is a sustainable production model with significant economic, social, and environmental benefits. However, its development faces three critical constraints: Consumers often misperceive remanufactured products as inferior secondhand items, leading to lower willingness to pay; Most Original Equipment Manufacturers (OEMs) prioritize new product R&D over remanufacturing; Intellectual property disputes between OEMs and remanufacturers hinder collaboration. Despite existing research on government subsidies and authorized remanufacturing, two key literature gaps remain: few studies integrate insurance institutions as independent decision-makers into remanufacturing supply chains, and consumer-targeted subsidies are treated as a homogeneous category, lacking differentiation. To address these, this study builds a supply chain with four stakeholders (OEM, Third-Party Remanufacturer/TPR, insurance institution, consumers) and develops Stackelberg game models for three subsidy strategies: subsidizing TPR (Model R), subsidizing all remanufactured-part-claim insurance (i.e., insurance where the insurance institution settles claims with remanufactured parts when consumers file claims due to product failures) buyers (Model B), and subsidizing consumers of remanufactured-part-claim insurance with valid claims (Model A). Our key results reveal two core findings: Model R and Model A have similar effects-both lead to equivalent equilibrium decisions and profits for supply chain members; When both the claims ratio and consumer acceptance of remanufactured products are high, Model B achieves a win-win situation: it boosts the remanufacturing market share and increases profits for the OEM, TPR, and insurance institution, while aligning with government sustainability goals. Provides a quantitative basis for governments to design targeted remanufacturing subsidy policies. Collectively, these findings provide a quantitative basis for governments to design targeted remanufacturing subsidy policies.
